hire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Briarcliff upon Hill, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Anglie","Hanthorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Hanthorpe, Lincolnshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1350–1383":"1350–1383","1351–1383":"1351–1383","1350–1391":"1350–1391","1370–1423":"1370–1423","1370–1429":"1370–1429","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1323–1405":"1323–1405","1325–1391":"1325–1391","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","1325":"1325","1423":"1423","1323":"1323","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Berkeleye, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Briarcliff upon Hill, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Hanthorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Hanthorpe, Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"1350–1383":"1350–1383","1351–1383":"1351–1383","1350–1391":"1350–1391","1370–1423":"1370–1423","1370–1429":"1370–1429","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1323–1405":"1323–1405","1325–1391":"1325–1391","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","1325":"1325","1423":"1423","1323":"1323","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Berkeleye, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Briarcliff upon Hill, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Hanthorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Hanthorpe, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"1350–1383":"1350–1383","1351–1383":"1351–1383","1350–1391":"1350–1391","1370–1423":"1370–1423","1370–1429":"1370–1429","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1323–1405":"1323–1405","1325–1391":"1325–1391","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","1325":"1325","1423":"1423","1323":"1323","1429":"1429","1405":"1405","Berkeleye, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Briarcliff upon Hill, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Hanthorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Hanthorpe, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Smythe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Smith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Smith","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name denoting a worker in metal, especially iron, such as a blacksmith or farrier, from Middle English <i>smith</i> ‘smith’ (Old English <i>smith</i>, probably a derivative of <i>smītan</i> ‘to strike, hammer’). Early examples are also found in the Latin form   Faber  . Metal-working was one of the earliest occupations for which specialist skills were required, and its importance ensured that this term and its equivalents in other languages were the most widespread of all occupational surnames in Europe. Medieval smiths were important not only in making horseshoes, plowshares, and other domestic articles, but above all for their skill in forging swords, other weapons, and armor. This is also the most frequent of all surnames in the US. It is very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below). This surname (in any of the two possible English senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti. See also   Smither  .","English: from Middle English <i>smithe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smiththe</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, occupational, for someone who worked in one, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Smitha in King's Nympton (Devon). Compare   Smithey  .","Irish and Scottish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b>, Irish <b>Mac Gabhann</b> ‘son of the smith’. See   McGowan  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Carrington","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, a local name from any of several places in England so named. The one in Gloucestershire is an Old English compound meaning ‘settlement of Beorn's people’. In the Somerset place name the first element is an unattested Old English personal name <i>Bāra</i>, which also occurs, in the genitive form, as the first element of the Cambridgeshire place name. <i>Barrington</i> has also been used as an English form of Gaelic <i>Ó Bearáin</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Carrington Smythe was born in 1350, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Carrington-Smythe, was 27 and his mother, Lady Caroline Ann Garvays, was 25. He married Anne Acthorpe. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1383, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 33, and was buried in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1350–1383":"1350–1383","1351–1383":"1351–1383","1350–1391":"1350–1391","1370–1423":"1370–1423","1370–1429":"1370–1429","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1323–1405":"1323–1405","1325–1391":"1325–1391","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1391"